Get data from the API and function to turn into dataframe

  • format is (symbol, interval, start, end, limit)
  • Pandas for dataframes
In [ ]:
def binanceDataFrame(klines):
    df = pd.DataFrame(klines.reshape(-1,12),dtype=float, columns = ('time', 'open', 'high', 'low', 'close', 'volume', 'close_time', ' quote_volume', 'count', 'taker_buy_volume', 'taker_buy_quote_volume', 'ignore'))
    df['time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['time'], unit='ms')
    
    return df


data = {}

for symbol in symbols:
    klines = np.array(client.get_historical_klines(symbol, interval, start, end))
    dataframe = binanceDataFrame(klines)
    data[symbol] = dataframe

Plot data using plotly

  • Plotly for plotting candlestick charts
In [12]:
def candlestickplot(df):
    fig = go.Figure(data=[go.Candlestick(x=df['time'],
                open=df['open'],
                high=df['high'],
                low=df['low'],
                close=df['close'])])
    
    return fig

figures = {}

for symbol in symbols:
    figures[symbol] = candlestickplot(data[symbol])

Running statistical analysis

  • Seaborn for data visualisation
In [49]:
closes_list = [data[symbol]['close'] for symbol in symbols]
closes = pd.concat(closes_list, axis = 1)
closes.columns = symbols

correlations = closes.corr()

matrix = np.triu(correlations)
heatmap = seaborn.heatmap(correlations, cmap="crest", annot = True, mask = matrix) ## plot a heatmap of the correlation between the close prices

In [88]:
def pairs_trading_test(a,b):
    model = LinearRegression().fit(np.array(closes[a]).reshape((-1,1)), np.array(closes[b]))
    difference = np.add(model.coef_ * closes[a] + model.intercept_, -closes[b])
    return adfuller(difference)

test = {}

for i in range(0,len(symbols)):
    for j in range(0,i):
        test[(symbols[j], symbols[i])] = pairs_trading_test(symbols[i], symbols[j])[1]

adfuller_pvalue = dict(sorted(test.items(), key = lambda item: item[1]))
adfuller_pvalue

There are also many pairs with a p-value below 0.05, meaning the difference between the pairs - scaled appropriately using linear regression - is likely stationary.¶

results = {}

    results[key] = [adfuller_pvalue[key], correlation[key]]
    
results = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(results, orient = 'index', columns = ['adfuller test p-value', 'correlation'])

Overall we can see there are 5 pairs which have both a correlation above 0.9 and p-value from the augmented Dicky-Fuller test below 0.05. Pairs trading with these pairs could be profitable due to these results and the relative immaturity of the cryptocurrency markets, which should result in more pricing inefficiences¶
